The '''British Military Administration''' ('''BMA''') was the [[interim]] administrator of [[British Borneo]] between the end of the [[Second World War]] and the establishment of the Crown Colonies of [[Crown Colony of Sarawak|Sarawak]] and [[Crown Colony of North Borneo|North Borneo]] in 1946. Specifically, the entity lasted from 12 September 1945 to 1 July 1946.<ref name="swk">{{cite web|url=http://www.sarawak.gov.my/web/home/article_view/237/248/|title=Sarawak as a British Crown Colony (1946 â€“ 1963)|publisher=Sarawak State Government|accessdate=4 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804113608/http://www.sarawak.gov.my/web/home/article_view/237/248/|archivedate=4 August 2017|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name="yust">{{cite book|author=Walter Yust|title=Ten eventful years: a record of events of the years preceding, including and following World War II, 1937 through 1946|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OJAGAQAAIAAJ|year=1947|publisher=Encyclopaedia Britannica|page=382}}</ref><ref name="bma">{{cite web|url=http://www.sabah.gov.my/ark/history.html|title=History (British Military Administration in Borneo)|publisher=The Sabah State Archives|work=Chief Minister's Department|accessdate=1 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430164412/http://www.sabah.gov.my/ark/history.html|archivedate=1 May 2014|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name="Thiessen2008">{{cite book|author=Tamara Thiessen|title=Borneo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g9sj_FMSMu8C&pg=PA211|year=2008|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-252-1|pages=211–}}</ref> [[Labuan]] became the headquarters of BMA. The headquarters was mostly managed by the [[Second Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF).<ref name="Gin2010"/>

== Administration ==
The area under this administration comprises today of [[Labuan]], [[Sabah]], [[Sarawak]] and [[Brunei]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Stephen R. Evans|title=Sabah (North Borneo): Under the Rising Sun Government|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=chxxAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Tropical Press}}</ref>

Sarawak was administered by Australians under British Borneo Civil Affairs Unit (BBCAU).<ref name="Hui Ling 2001">{{cite journal|last1=Ho|first1=Hui Ling|title=PENYERAHAN SARAWAK KEPADA KERAJAAN BRITISH, 1946-l951 (Cession of Sarawak to the British (1946 to 1951)|journal=Persatuan Sejarah Malaysia (Malaysian Historical Society)|date=2001|volume=9|issue=4|pages=43–73|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517021919/http://myrepositori.pnm.gov.my/bitstream/123456789/1326/1/MDSS_2001_Bil29_04.pdf|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>

